===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|p}} – a kneeling man or figure with an ugly face ([[甶]]). The ugly face could be a mask. The lower right “dot” is a small {{zh-l|*厶}}; it is a residual tail that was added later – compare {{zh-l|*离}}. Related to [[畏]] (variant [[𠂽]]), which originally depicts a ghost standing with a stick in hand.

Compare {{zh-l|*異|different, strange}}, in which the {{zh-l|*田}} also derives from a face and indicates a mask. Compare also [[禺]], in which the top component represents either a mask or a monkey's head.

===Etymology===
{{unk|zh}}. May be related to: 
* {{och-l|威|to overawe, to terrorise}} with ''k''-nominalisation and endoactive tone B, ''lit.'' "the thing which is doing the overawing" (Childs-Johnson, 1995 apud {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter & Sagart, 2014}}), or 
* {{och-l|歸|to return}} ({{w|Shuowen Jiezi}} [https://ctext.org/shuo-wen-jie-zi/gui-bu?searchu=%E6%AD%B8&searchmode=showall#result]; {{w|Liezi}} [https://ctext.org/liezi/tian-rui?searchu=%E9%AC%BC%E6%AD%B8%E4%B9%9F&searchmode=showall#result]; Carr, 1985 apud {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}), yet {{zh-ref|Baxter & Sagart (2014)}} consider this connection, while semantically plausible, to be a folk etymology; as {{och-l|鬼|tr=*k-ʔujʔ}} and {{och-l|歸|tr=*[k]ʷəj}} had different Old Chinese rhymes & thus were likely unrelated. 
See also {{och-l|詭|to deceive; peculiar}}. Note also similarities to {{cog|my|ကွယ်|t=to hide, obstruct}}.

